Posted: Fri Jun 14, 2013 7:38 am
"Since making encryption the default is in most cases impractical, most users of encrypted mail will be better served by encrypting only sensitive communications."I've got to object to that recommendation. Only encrypting "sensitive" stuff is like broadcasting "Look here! Look here!" when those persons from whom you're trying to hide your communications do end up with possession. That's especially true since the meta data is not encrypted. You're broadcasting when and where you're emailing sensitive information.If you really want to hide information but leave it on a public server you'll need to establish several different public keys and fill your inbox with mail to each. That will require the snooper to break several private keys to get to the "good stuff."
